{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "02 — Goroutines, Channels & Select",
  "description": "Go's signature feature: lightweight concurrency through goroutines and channels. This tour traces a single streaming model response through KronkClient and OpenAIClient, explaining every concurrent construct as it appears.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/kronk.go",
      "line": 20,
      "title": "2.1 — Struct with a mutex",
      "description": "```go\ntype KronkClient struct {\n    ChatModelFiles  []string\n    EmbedModelFiles []string\n    mu      sync.Mutex\n    chatKrn *kronk.Kronk\n    embKrn  *kronk.Kronk\n}\n```\n\n`sync.Mutex` is Go's mutual exclusion lock. The lowercase `mu`, `chatKrn`, `embKrn` fields are unexported — callers outside the `llm` package can't access them. They're internal implementation detail.\n\nThe mutex is needed because `KronkClient` is used from a goroutine, and the `instance()` method below initialises `chatKrn`/`embKrn` lazily. Without a mutex, two concurrent requests could both see `nil` and both try to initialise — a data race."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/kronk.go",
      "line": 30,
      "title": "2.2 — Mutex lock/unlock with defer",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (c *KronkClient) instance(slot **kronk.Kronk, ...) (*kronk.Kronk, error) {\n    c.mu.Lock()\n    defer c.mu.Unlock()\n    if *slot != nil {\n        return *slot, nil\n    }\n    ...\n}\n```\n\n`c.mu.Lock()` acquires the mutex — only one goroutine can be past this line at a time. `defer c.mu.Unlock()` releases it when the function returns, no matter how.\n\nThis is the canonical Go mutex pattern: **lock immediately, defer unlock immediately**. The `defer` ensures you can never forget to unlock even if you add an early return later.\n\n`slot **kronk.Kronk` is a pointer to a pointer — the method receives the address of `c.chatKrn` or `c.embKrn` so it can write through to the field. `*slot != nil` dereferences it to check whether initialisation is done; `*slot = krn` writes the result back."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/kronk.go",
      "line": 112,
      "title": "2.3 — Creating a buffered channel",
      "description": "```go\nch := make(chan Chunk, 8)\n```\n\nA **channel** is a typed, goroutine-safe pipe. `make(chan Chunk, 8)` creates a **buffered** channel with capacity 8: up to 8 `Chunk` values can sit in the pipe before a send blocks.\n\nWhy buffered? Without a buffer, every `ch <- chunk` would block until the caller reads. A small buffer lets the goroutine run slightly ahead of the reader — useful when the model produces tokens faster than the HTTP handler can flush them.\n\nThe return type of `ChatStream` is `<-chan Chunk` (receive-only). The method creates the full `chan Chunk` internally, hands out the restricted view, and keeps the write end inside the goroutine. It's a compile-time access-control contract."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/kronk.go",
      "line": 113,
      "title": "2.4 — Launching a goroutine",
      "description": "```go\ngo func() {\n    defer close(ch)\n    ...\n}()\nreturn ch, nil\n```\n\n`go` launches a **goroutine**: a cooperatively-scheduled lightweight thread managed by the Go runtime. Creating one costs about 2KB of stack — you can have tens of thousands. The `func() { ... }()` is a function literal called immediately; `go` in front means \"start it, don't wait for it.\"\n\n`ChatStream` returns `ch` immediately — the goroutine is still running in the background. The caller gets a channel they can read from as tokens arrive.\n\n`defer close(ch)` is the critical safety guarantee: **when the goroutine exits (for any reason), the channel closes**. Anything doing `for chunk := range ch` will exit the loop when the channel closes. Without this, the range loop would wait forever."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/kronk.go",
      "line": 116,
      "title": "2.5 — Ranging over a channel",
      "description": "```go\nfor resp := range src {\n    ...\n}\n```\n\n`for v := range ch` reads from a channel until it is **closed**. This is identical to what the agent loop does when it reads from Balaur's `ch` — the same pattern appears at two levels of the stack.\n\nHere `src` is Kronk's own channel (from `krn.ChatStreaming`). This goroutine bridges between Kronk's model response type and Balaur's `Chunk` type — translating fields and forwarding to `ch`.\n\n**The data flow so far:**\n```\nKronk goroutine  → src (kronk channel)\n                     ↓\nour goroutine    reads src, translates, writes ch\n                     ↓\nagent.Loop       reads ch via for-range\n```\nEach arrow is a channel crossing a goroutine boundary, all safely typed."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/kronk.go",
      "line": 129,
      "title": "2.6 — Select for cancellation (the most important pattern)",
      "description": "```go\nselect {\ncase ch <- Chunk{Content: delta.Content, Reasoning: delta.Reasoning}:\ncase <-ctx.Done():\n    ch <- Chunk{Err: ctx.Err()}\n    return\n}\n```\n\n`select` is Go's switch-for-channels. It waits until **one of the cases is ready**, then executes it. If both are ready at once, it picks randomly.\n\nWhat this says:\n- Try to send a chunk into `ch`. If the reader is keeping up, this case fires.\n- If the `context` was cancelled (HTTP request closed, user navigated away, timeout hit), `ctx.Done()` closes, this case fires instead — we send an error chunk and exit the goroutine.\n\nWithout `select`, a cancelled context would leave the goroutine blocked on `ch <-` forever (if nobody is reading), leaking memory until the process dies.\n\nThis pattern appears identically in `openai.go` at line 163. It's the canonical Go cancellation idiom — you'll see it in every production Go networking code."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/openai.go",
      "line": 124,
      "title": "2.7 — The same pattern in the HTTP client",
      "description": "```go\nch := make(chan Chunk, 8)\ngo func() {\n    defer close(ch)\n    defer resp.Body.Close()\n    ...\n}()\nreturn ch, nil\n```\n\nNotice `OpenAIClient.ChatStream` is structurally identical to `KronkClient.ChatStream` — same channel, same goroutine, same defer pattern. The `Client` interface in `llm.go` forced them to have the same shape, so the agent loop can use either without modification.\n\nThe extra `defer resp.Body.Close()` here cleans up the HTTP response body. In Go, HTTP response bodies must be explicitly closed or they leak a connection. `defer` ensures this runs whether the goroutine exits normally or via `return` from the select."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/openai.go",
      "line": 131,
      "title": "2.8 — SSE line-by-line parsing",
      "description": "```go\nsc := bufio.NewScanner(resp.Body)\nsc.Buffer(make([]byte, 0, 64*1024), 4*1024*1024)\nfor sc.Scan() {\n    line := strings.TrimSpace(sc.Text())\n    if !strings.HasPrefix(line, \"data:\") {\n        continue\n    }\n    data := strings.TrimSpace(strings.TrimPrefix(line, \"data:\"))\n    if data == \"[DONE]\" {\n        break\n    }\n    ...\n```\n\nServer-Sent Events (SSE) is a text protocol: the server sends lines like `data: {\"choices\":[...]}` and a `data: [DONE]` at the end. `bufio.NewScanner` reads the response body line by line.\n\n`sc.Buffer(...)` sets a larger internal buffer — default is 64KB which is too small for responses with long tool-call argument strings.\n\nThis is the only place in Balaur that does raw HTTP parsing. Everything else talks to clean Go types. Notice that once tokens are extracted from the SSE lines and sent into `ch`, the agent loop consumes them exactly the same way it consumes Kronk tokens — the channel is the abstraction boundary.\n\n**Exercise:** Change `sc.Buffer(make([]byte, 0, 64*1024), 4*1024*1024)` to `sc.Buffer(make([]byte, 0, 1), 1)` and send a very long message. What error do you get? Restore it after."
    }
  ]
}
